{"title_page": "Willaston, Cheshire East", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country                  = England\n| coordinates              = {{coord|53.082|-2.479|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name            = Willaston\n| label_position           = top\n| population               = 3,104\n| population_ref           = (2011)\n| static_image             = Willaston Mike Heywood Green.jpg\n| static_image_caption     = Mike Heywood Green Willaston\n| shire_district           = \n| unitary_england          = [[Cheshire East]]\n| shire_county             = [[Cheshire]]\n| region                   = North West England\n| civil_parish             = Willaston\n| constituency_westminster = [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]]\n| postcode_district        = CW5\n| postcode_area            = CW\n| post_town                = Crewe\n| dial_code                = 01270 (Crewe)\n| os_grid_reference        = SJ682539\n| london_distance          = \n}}\n'''Willaston''' is a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and village in the unitary authority of [[Cheshire East]] and the ceremonial county of [[Cheshire]], in north-west [[England]]. It has a population of 2,277<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/ |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref> people according to the 2001 [[census]], increasing to 3,104 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11130674&c=Willaston&d=16&e=62&g=6407854&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458056475214&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=15 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nIt is approximately three miles west of [[Crewe]] town centre and two miles east of [[Nantwich]] town centre. Willaston has very good transport links being approximately 7 miles from junction 16 of the M6 and 3 miles from [[Crewe railway station]]. \n\n==Governance==\nFrom 1974 to 2009 the Borough Council was [[Crewe and Nantwich]]. Since this was abolished on 1 April 2009, the civil parish has been administered by the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Cheshire East]].<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080634_en_2#pt2-l1g3 Cheshire (Structural Changes) Order 2008]</ref> \n\nWillaston Parish Council was established in 1894 and is responsible for the management of the Lettie Spencer Playing Field, The War Memorial on Colleys Lane, the village allotments on Crewe Road, The Spinney off Coppice Road and Mike Heywood Green. The Council is made up of 12 members from two wards who represent the interests of all Willaston Residents.<ref>[https://www.willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/ Willaston Parish Council], Willason Parish Council Website. Retrieved: 30 October 2019.</ref> \n\nWillaston falls in the parliamentary constituency of [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]],<ref>[http://maps.cheshire.gov.uk/cheshirecc.interactivemapping.web.internet/Default.aspx?e=370949&n=351148&mpp=25&layers=BOU.PLA.PLO.PAR.WCON&hLayer=WCON&hField=OBJECTID&hValue=19 Cheshire County Council: Interactive Mapping: Crewe and Nantwich]. Retrieved 27 January 2009.</ref> which has been represented by [[Kieran Mullan]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]].\n\n== History of Willaston ==\nWillaston is believed to have taken its name from an ancient farmstead known as Wiglaf's tun. Like other English villages, the name has been changed many times over the centuries. This is due to the neighbouring parish of Wistaston having a similar sounding name. To add confusion, Willaston was once ecclesiastically divided between the neighbouring communities of Nantwich and Wybunbury.\n\nWhilst there are at least two other villages called Willaston, the earliest documentary evidence relating to Willaston in this part of Cheshire can be found in the [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] survey of 1086, where is it referred to as Wilavestune. We know by reading this document that a 'free man' by the name of Ulviet once owned Wilvastune and that, just a few years after the Norman conquest, the title passed to Willam Malbank. The manor of Wilvastune remained in the Malbank family for several generations before ownership transferred to the Chanu family in the 13th century.\n\nAt this time, Willaston was a remote, sparsely populated community with no village centre. Nevertheless, it covered a much larger area than it does today, stretching from Newcastle Road and London Road Nantwich in the south, along Millstone Lane and as far as the ancient grazing land of Beam Heath in the north. These boundaries did not change until 1936, when local government decided to transfer some of Willaston's land to the expanding communities of [[Nantwich]] and Stapeley. In 1553, the manor of Willaston was bought by Richard Sneyd. Recorder of Chester. The Sneyd family lived at [[Keele Hall]] in Staffordshire and were the major landowners in WIllaston until the middle of the 19th century. \n\nAlthough Willaston had a number of farmsteads in the middle ages, most of the surrounding landscape was uncultivated. However, this began to change as more and more common land began to fall into private ownership during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The process (known as 'enclosure') brought major changes to rural communities such as Willaston, as individual plots of land were fenced off and used for arable farming, meadows and the grazing of livestock. The Sneyd family were absentee landlords but they owned most of the lands in Willaston from 1533 to the late 19th century. \n\nUnfortunately, the medieval moated site of the Chanu family was lost during the construction of the Nantwich by-pass in 1989. It was situated to the south-east of the Old Willaston Board School on land now owned by Cheerbrook Farm. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/files/Willaston_Parish_Plan_2009.pdf|title=Willaston Parish Plan - History of Willaston|last=|first=|date=|website=Willaston Parish Council|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities==\nThe village centre of Willaston has two [[public house]]s (The Lamb and The Nag's Head) and a social club, while an [[off-licence]] provides local produce and day to day goods. Another pub, The Peacock, is situated to the north-west of the village centre, on Crewe Road (the [[A534 road|A534]]). Alongside The Peacock pub is a hotel operated by [[Premier Inn]].\n \nThe social club offers many social events ranging from a monthly kids disco to various tribute bands and acts.  The club has two pool teams, a [[snooker]] team, two 7-a-side [[Association football|football]] teams, a darts and [[dominoes]] team and a ladies [[darts]] team. In summer 2013 the function room (available for hire) was refurbished.\n\nThe village also has a fish and chip shop, and hairdressing salons. There are local businesses within the village providing employment (Scanlans, SJB Steel). At the edge of the village is a farm shop, Cheerbrook,<ref>[http://www.cheerbrook.co.uk Cheerbrook Farm's Official Website] . Retrieved 31 January 2009.</ref> on the Newcastle Road. A plant nursery and garden centre is located on Crewe Road.\n\nWillaston Primary School<ref>[http://clc2.uniservity.com/Grouphomepage.asp?GroupId=71339 Willaston Primary School Website] . Retrieved May 18th 2010.</ref> is the only education establishment in the village. For children of pre-school age, there is an Ofsted registered playgroup in the village.\n\nA [[Red telephone box|K6]] telephone box is located in the village on Wistaston Road and has been in place since the late 1940's. The box was decommissioned by [[BT Group|British Telecom]] in 2010. The telephone box was purchased by Willaston Parish Council and turned into a book exchange known as the book box. A restoration was carried out in September 2019.\n[[File:Willaston_Book_Box.jpg|thumb|Former K6 Telephone box converted into a book exchange box]]\n\n==Local events==\n[[File:Willaston - Worm Charming.jpg|thumb|right|The [[World Worm Charming Championships]] have been held in Willaston since 1980.]]\nOne of the major events in Willaston is the [[World Worm Charming Championships]]. It was started in 1980 by John Bailey. The event attracts many competitors from around the world, from the U.S. to Australia. The original event in 1980 was won with a total of 511 worms by Tom Shufflebotham - a record that stood until 2009.\n\nCelebrities that have taken part in the championships include [[Ben Fogle]] and [[Bob Carolgees]]. In 2008 celebrity contestants [[Paddy McGuinness]] and [[Rory McGrath]] filmed a slot for their series \"Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demand.five.tv/Episode.aspx?episodeBaseName=C5141230003 |title=Demand Five &#124; watch Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure, Series 1 - episode 3, Episode 3 |publisher=Demand.five.tv |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 championship was won by Mike and Claire Gaukroger with a total of 125 worms; the trophy for the heaviest worm went to Ray O'Grady and Steve Plant (4.6g).<ref>{{cite web |author=Nicola King on behalf of I.F.C.W.A.P. |url=http://www.wormcharming.com |title=The World Worm Charming Championships |publisher=Wormcharming.com |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504122657/http://www.wormcharming.com/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, due to particularly good conditions, three teams broke the previous world record of 511. Sophie Smith and Matt Smith of Willaston claimed the title with a total of 567 worms in 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5664058/The-charms-of-worm-charming.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=The charms of worm charming | first=William | last=Langley | date=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Willaston Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Willaston, Cheshire East}}\n\n{{Cheshire, Cheshire East}}\n{{Cheshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cheshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{More citations needed|date=June 2009}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n| country = England\n| coordinates = {{coord|53.082|-2.479|display=inline,title}}\n| official_name = Willaston\n| label_position = top\n| population = 3,104\n| population_ref = (2011)\n| static_image = [[File:Willaston Mike Heywood Green.jpg|thumb|Mike Heywood Green lcated at the junction of Wistaston Road and Moorfields]]\n| static_image_caption = Mike Heywood Green Willaston\n| shire_district = \n| unitary_england = [[Cheshire East]]\n| shire_county = [[Cheshire]]\n| region = North West England\n| civil_parish = Willaston\n| constituency_westminster = [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]]\n| postcode_district = CW5\n| postcode_area = CW\n| post_town = Crewe\n| dial_code = 01270 (Crewe)\n| os_grid_reference = SJ682539\n| london_distance = \n}}\n'''Willaston''' is a [[civil parishes in England|civil parish]] and village in the unitary authority of [[Cheshire East]] and the ceremonial county of [[Cheshire]], in north-west [[England]]. It has a population of 2,277<ref>{{cite web|author=Neighbourhood Statistics |url=http://neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/ |title=Check Browser Settings |publisher=Neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref> people according to the 2001 [[census]], increasing to 3,104 at the 2011 Census.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadKeyFigures.do?a=7&b=11130674&c=Willaston&d=16&e=62&g=6407854&i=1001x1003x1032x1004&m=0&r=1&s=1458056475214&enc=1|title=Civil Parish population 2011|accessdate=15 March 2016|publisher=Office for National Statistics|work=Neighbourhood Statistics}}</ref>\n\nIt is approximately three miles west of [[Crewe]] town centre and two miles east of [[Nantwich]] town centre. Willaston has very good transport links being approximately 7 miles from junction 16 of the M6 and 3 miles from [[Crewe railway station]]. \n\n==Governance==\nFrom 1974 to 2009 the Borough Council was [[Crewe and Nantwich]]. Since this was abolished on 1 April 2009, the civil parish has been administered by the new [[unitary authority]] of [[Cheshire East]].<ref>[http://www.opsi.gov.uk/si/si2008/uksi_20080634_en_2#pt2-l1g3 Cheshire (Structural Changes) Order 2008]</ref> \n\nWillaston Parish Council was established in 1894 and is responsible for the management of the Lettie Spencer Playing Field, The War Memorial on Colleys Lane, the village allotments on Crewe Road, The Spinney off Coppice Road and Mike Heywood Green. The Council is made up of 12 members from two wards who represent the interests of all Willaston Residents.<ref>[https://www.willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/ Willaston Parish Council], Willason Parish Council Website. Retrieved: 30 October 2019.</ref> \n\nWillaston falls in the parliamentary constituency of [[Crewe and Nantwich (UK Parliament constituency)|Crewe and Nantwich]],<ref>[http://maps.cheshire.gov.uk/cheshirecc.interactivemapping.web.internet/Default.aspx?e=370949&n=351148&mpp=25&layers=BOU.PLA.PLO.PAR.WCON&hLayer=WCON&hField=OBJECTID&hValue=19 Cheshire County Council: Interactive Mapping: Crewe and Nantwich] . Retrieved 27 January 2009.</ref> which has been represented by [[Kieran Mullan]] since the [[2019 United Kingdom general election|2019 General Election]].\n\n== History of Willaston ==\nWillaston is believed to have taken its name from an ancient farmstead known as Wiglaf's tun. Like other English villages, the name has been changed many times over the centuries. This is due to the neighbouring parish of Wistaston having a similar sounding name. To add confusion, Willaston was once ecclesiastically divided between the neighbouring communities of Nantwich and Wybunbury.\n\n\n\nWhilst there are at least two other villages called Willaston, the earliest documentary evidence relating to Willaston in this part of Cheshire can be found in the [[Domesday Book|Domesday]] survey of 1086, where is it referred to as Wilavestune. We know by reading this document that a 'free man' by the name of Ulviet once owned Wilvastune and that, just a few years after the Norman conquest, the title passed to Willam Malbank. The manor of Wilvastune remained in the Malbank family for several generations before ownership transferred to the Chanu family in the 13th century.\n\nAt this time, Willaston was a remote, sparsely populated community with no village centre. Nevertheless, it covered a much larger area than it does today, stretching from Newcastle Road and London Road Nantwich in the south, along Millstone Lane and as far as the ancient grazing land of Beam Heath in the north. These boundaries did not change until 1936, when local government decided to transfer some of Willaston's land to the expanding communities of [[Nantwich]] and Stapeley. In 1553, the manor of Willaston was bought by Richard Sneyd. Recorder of Chester. The Sneyd family lived at [[Keele Hall]] in Staffordshire and were the major landowners in WIllaston until the middle of the 19th century. \n\nAlthough Willaston had a number of farmsteads in the middle ages, most of the surrounding landscape was uncultivated. However, this began to change as more and more common land began to fall into private ownership during the late 18th and early 19th centuries. The process (known as 'enclosure') brought major changes to rural communities such as Willaston, as individual plots of land were fenced off and used for arable farming, meadows and the grazing of livestock. The Sneyd family were absentee landlords but they owned most of the lands in Willaston from 1533 to the late 19th century. \n\nUnfortunately, the medieval moated site of the Chanu family was lost during the construction of the Nantwich by-pass in 1989. It was situated to the south-east of the Old Willaston Board School on land now owned by Cheerbrook Farm. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://willastonparishcouncil.org.uk/files/Willaston_Parish_Plan_2009.pdf|title=Willaston Parish Plan - History of Willaston|last=|first=|date=|website=Willaston Parish Council|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Local amenities==\nThe village centre of Willaston has two [[public house]]s (The Lamb and The Nag's Head) and a social club, while an [[off-licence]] provides local produce and day to day goods. Another pub, The Peacock, is situated to the north-west of the village centre, on Crewe Road (the [[A534 road|A534]]). Alongside The Peacock pub is a hotel operated by [[Premier Inn]].\n \nThe social club offers many social events ranging from a monthly kids disco to various tribute bands and acts.  The club has two pool teams, a [[snooker]] team, two 7-a-side [[Association football|football]] teams, a darts and [[dominoes]] team and a ladies [[darts]] team. In summer 2013 the function room (available for hire) was refurbished.\n\nThe village also has a fish and chip shop, and hairdressing salons. There are local businesses within the village providing employment (Scanlans, SJB Steel). At the edge of the village is a farm shop, Cheerbrook,<ref>[http://www.cheerbrook.co.uk Cheerbrook Farm's Official Website] . Retrieved 31 January 2009.</ref> on the Newcastle Road. A plant nursery and garden centre is located on Crewe Road.\n\nWillaston Primary School<ref>[http://clc2.uniservity.com/Grouphomepage.asp?GroupId=71339 Willaston Primary School Website] . Retrieved May 18th 2010.</ref> is the only education establishment in the village. For children of pre-school age, there is an Ofsted registered playgroup in the village.\n\nA [[Red telephone box|K6]] telephone box is located in the village on Wistaston Road and has been in place since the late 1940's. The box was decommissioned by [[BT Group|British Telecom]] in 2010. The telephone box was purchased by Willaston Parish Council and turned into a book exchange known as the book box. A restoration was carried out in September 2019.\n[[File:Willaston_Book_Box.jpg|thumb|Former K6 Telephone box converted into a book exchange box]]\n\n==Local events==\n[[File:Willaston - Worm Charming.jpg|thumb|right|The [[World Worm Charming Championships]] have been held in Willaston since 1980.]]\nOne of the major events in Willaston is the [[World Worm Charming Championships]]. It was started in 1980 by John Bailey. The event attracts many competitors from around the world, from the U.S. to Australia. The original event in 1980 was won with a total of 511 worms by Tom Shufflebotham - a record that stood until 2009.\n\nCelebrities that have taken part in the championships include [[Ben Fogle]] and [[Bob Carolgees]]. In 2008 celebrity contestants [[Paddy McGuinness]] and [[Rory McGrath]] filmed a slot for their series \"Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://demand.five.tv/Episode.aspx?episodeBaseName=C5141230003 |title=Demand Five &#124; watch Rory & Paddy's Great British Adventure, Series 1 - episode 3, Episode 3 |publisher=Demand.five.tv |date= |accessdate=2009-06-30}}</ref>\n\nThe 2008 championship was won by Mike and Claire Gaukroger with a total of 125 worms; the trophy for the heaviest worm went to Ray O'Grady and Steve Plant (4.6g).<ref>{{cite web |author=Nicola King on behalf of I.F.C.W.A.P. |url=http://www.wormcharming.com |title=The World Worm Charming Championships |publisher=Wormcharming.com |accessdate=2009-06-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090504122657/http://www.wormcharming.com/ |archivedate=2009-05-04 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2009, due to particularly good conditions, three teams broke the previous world record of 511. Sophie Smith and Matt Smith of Willaston claimed the title with a total of 567 worms in 30 minutes.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/5664058/The-charms-of-worm-charming.html | work=The Daily Telegraph | location=London | title=The charms of worm charming | first=William | last=Langley | date=28 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Cheshire}}\n*[[Willaston Hall]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category-inline|Willaston, Cheshire East}}\n\n{{Cheshire, Cheshire East}}\n{{Cheshire}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Cheshire]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes in Cheshire]]\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willaston,_Cheshire_East"}
{"title_page": "Jules Dassin", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jules Dassin\n| image         = Joe and Jules Dassin 1970.jpg\n| caption       = Jules Dassin (right) with son Joe in Paris in 1970\n| birthname     = Julius Dassin\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1911|12|18}}\n| birth_place    = [[Middletown, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2008|3|31|1911|12|18}}\n| death_place    = [[Athens]], Greece\n| spouse        = {{marriage|B\u00e9atrice Launer<br>|1937|1962|end=divorced}}<br> {{marriage|[[Melina Mercouri]]<br>|1966|1994|end=died}}\n| children = [[Joe Dassin|Joseph Ira Dassin]]<br/>Richelle Dassin<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Julie Dassin|fr}}\n}}\n'''Julius''' \"'''Jules'''\" '''Dassin''' (December 18, 1911 \u2013 March 31, 2008) was an American film director, producer, writer and actor. He was a subject of the [[Hollywood blacklist]] in the [[Joseph McCarthy|McCarthy]] era, and subsequently moved to France, where he revived his career.\n\n== Biography ==\n===Early life===\nDassin was born in [[Middletown, Connecticut]], one of eight children of Berthe Vogel and Samuel Dassin, a barber. His parents were both [[Jewish]] immigrants from [[Odessa]], in modern-day [[Ukraine]].<ref>David B. Green, [https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/1911-director-who-paris-adored-is-born-1.5378392 This Day in Jewish History 1911: Blacklisted Director Who Became the Toast of Paris Is Born], [[Haaretz]], 18 December 2015. Retrieved 30 May 2018.</ref> Dassin grew up in Harlem and went to [[Morris High School (Bronx)|Morris High School]] in the [[Bronx]]. During his youth he attended [[Camp Kinderland]], the left-wing Yiddish youth camp. He joined the [[Communist Party USA]] in the 1930s and left it after the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] in 1939. \n\n===Early career===\nDassin started as an actor with the ARTEF (''[[Yiddish theatre|Yiddish Proletarian Theater]]'') company in New York. He collaborated on a film with [[Jack Skurnick]] that was uncompleted because of Skurnick's early death.\n\nIn 1940 he moved to Hollywood and became an assistant director at [[RKO Pictures]] before moving to [[MGM]] where he made short films including ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'' (1941) which led to him being promoted to direct feature films.<ref>{{cite book | last = Katz | first = Ephraim | title = The Macmillan International Film Encyclopedia | publisher = Macmillan | location = New York | year = 1998 | isbn = 0-333-74037-8 |oclc=39216574 |edition=3rd |page=333}}</ref>\n\nDassin quickly became better known for his [[film noir|noir films]] ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947), ''[[The Naked City]]'' (1948), and ''[[Thieves' Highway]]'' (1949), which helped him to become regarded as \"one of the leading American filmmakers of the postwar era.\"<ref name=\"Luther\">{{cite news|last=Luther|first=Claudia|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/apr/01/local/me-dassin1|title=Noir master directed caper classic 'Rififi'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Hollywood Blacklist===\n{{Main|Hollywood Blacklist}}\nDassin said [[Darryl F. Zanuck]] in 1948 called him into his office to inform him he would be blacklisted, but he still had enough time to make a movie for Fox.<ref>''[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]'', [[Dan Georgakas]], spring 2007, p.72</ref>\nDassin was blacklisted in Hollywood during the production of ''[[Night and the City]]'' (1950).<ref>The film was shot in 1949, see {{cite web|last=Duncan|first=Paul|url=http://www.port-magazine.com/film/why-i-love-night-and-the-city-1950/|title=Why I Love: Night and the City (1950)|work=Port|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref> He was not allowed on the studio property to edit or oversee the musical score for the film.<ref name=\"dassin_interview\">{{cite AV media|last=Dassin|first=Jules|medium=post-screening interview in DVD supplements|title=[[Night and the City]]|publisher=[[Criterion Collection]]|date=February 1, 2005}}</ref> He also had trouble finding work abroad, as U.S. distribution companies blacklisted the U.S. distribution of any European film associated with artists blacklisted in Hollywood. In 1952, after Dassin had been out of work for two years, actress [[Bette Davis]] hired him to direct her in the Broadway revue ''[[Two's Company (musical)|Two's Company]]''. The show closed early, however, and Dassin left for Europe. \n\n===Move to Europe===\nDassin did not work as a film director again until ''[[Rififi]]'' in 1955 (a French production), his most influential film and an early work in the [[heist film|\"heist film\" genre]].  He won the Best Director award for the film at the 1955 [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n\nIt inspired later heist films, such as ''[[Ocean's Eleven (1960 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' (1960).<ref name=\"Luther\"/> Another film it  inspired was Dassin's own heist film ''[[Topkapi (film)|Topkapi]]'' (1964), filmed in France and [[Istanbul, Turkey]] with his future second wife, [[Melina Mercouri]] and Oscar winner [[Peter Ustinov]].\n\nMost of Dassin's films in the decades following the blacklist are European productions.<ref name=\"Luther\"/> His prolific later career in Europe and the affiliation with Greece through his second wife, combined with a common pronunciation of his surname as \"Da-SAN\" in Europe, as opposed to \"DASS-in\" in the United States leads to a common misconception that he was a European director.<ref name=\"dassin_interview\"/>\n\n===Melina Mercouri===\nAt the Cannes Film Festival in May 1955 he met Melina Mercouri, Greek actress and wife of Panos Harokopos.<ref name=\"Luther\"/> At about the same time, he discovered the literary works of [[Nikos Kazantzakis]]; these two elements created a bond with Greece. Dassin next made ''[[He Who Must Die]]'' (1957) based on Kazantzakis' ''[[Christ Recrucified]]'' and in which Mercouri appeared. She went on to star in his ''[[Never on Sunday]]'' (1960) for which she won best actress at the Cannes Film Festival.<ref name=Skainews>{{in lang|el}} [http://www.skai.gr/master_story.php?id=77340 Skai News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717003130/http://www.skai.gr/master_story.php?id=77340 |date=July 17, 2011 }}, \u0391\u03c0\u03b5\u03b2\u03af\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bf \u0396\u03c5\u03bb \u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03ad\u03bd (''Jules Dassin died''), [http://www.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.skai.gr%2Fmaster_story.php%3Fid%3D77340&langpair=el%7Cen&ie=UTF8 English (machine translation)] Retrieved on April 1, 2008.</ref> She then starred in his next three films \u2013 ''[[Phaedra (film)|Phaedra]]'' (1962), ''[[Topkapi (film)|Topkapi]]'' (1964) and ''[[10:30 P.M. Summer]]'' (1966).\n\nHe divorced his first wife, B\u00e9atrice Launer, in 1962 and married Mercouri in 1966. She later starred in his ''[[Promise at Dawn]]'' (1970).  During filming, Dassin broke both his legs.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|page=2|date=October 8, 1969|title=Dassin Breaks Both Legs In Freak Studio Accident}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliation with Greece===\nDassin was considered a major [[Philhellene]] to the point of Greek officials describing him as a \"first generation Greek\". Along with Mercouri, he opposed the [[Greek military junta]]. \n\nThe couple had to leave Greece after the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u201374|colonels' coup]] in 1967. In 1970 they were accused of having financed an attempt to overthrow the dictatorship, but the charges were quickly dropped.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Dassin and Mercouri lived in New York City during the 1970s; then, when the military dictatorship in Greece fell in 1974, they returned to Greece and lived out their lives there. In 1974 he and Mercouri made ''[[The Rehearsal (1974 film)|The Rehearsal]]'' about the junta. \n\nWhile Mercouri became involved with politics and won a parliamentary seat, Dassin stayed with movie-making in Europe. In 1982 he was a member of the jury at the [[34th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1984/04_jury_1984/04_Jury_1984.html |title=Berlinale: 1984 Juries |accessdate=November 21, 2010 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nDassin died from complications of [[influenza]] at the age of 96; he was survived by his two daughters and his grandchildren. Upon his death, the Greek prime minister, [[Costas Karamanlis]], released a statement: \"Greece mourns the loss of a rare human being, a significant artist and true friend. His passion, his relentless creative energy, his fighting spirit and his nobility will remain unforgettable.\"<ref name=\"Luther\"/>\n\nA major supporter of the return of the [[Elgin Marbles|Parthenon Marbles]] to Athens, for which he established the ''Melina Mercouri Institution'' in her memory after her death in 1994, he died a few months before the opening ceremony of the [[New Acropolis Museum]].<ref name=Skainews/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Dasin family 1970.jpg|thumb|Joe and Jules Dassin with B\u00e9atrice Launer in Paris in 1970]]\nDassin was married twice.  Prior to his marriage to Mercouri, in 1937 he married [[B\u00e9atrice Launer]], a New York\u2013born, {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Jewish\u2013American {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} violinist (aka Beatrice Launer-Dassin; 1913\u20131994),<ref>[http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:112F47BE008D2836 Beatrice Dassin]. Genealogy Bank. Retrieved on July 26, 2015.</ref> a graduate of the [[Juilliard School]] of Music.<ref>[http://www.juilliard.edu/libraryarchives/pdfs/baton/LoRes/V10N8low.pdf The Juilliard School of Music, \"The Baton\", p. 12] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528000637/http://www.juilliard.edu/libraryarchives/pdfs/baton/LoRes/V10N8low.pdf |date=May 28, 2010 }}</ref> They divorced in 1962. Their children were Joseph Ira Dassin, better known as [[Joe Dassin]] (1938\u201380), a popular French singer in the 1970s; songwriter Richelle \"Rickie\" Dassin (born 1940); and actress\u2013singer Julie Dassin (born 1944; also known as Julie D.).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120728181518/http://rateyourmusic.com/artist/julie_d_ Julie D.]. Rateyourmusic.com (July 19, 1945). Retrieved on July 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n* Bulleted list item\n==Preservation==\nThe Academy Film Archive has preserved Jules Dassin's film ''Night and the City'', including the British and pre-release versions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=&filmmaker=jules+dassin&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rialto pictures restored and released ''Rififi'' theatrically.  It was subsequently released on home video through [[The Criterion Collection]] and [[Arrow Films]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! colspan=\"6\"|Credited as\n|-\n! width=65 | [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=65 | [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=65 |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=65 |[[Actor]]\n! Role\n! Notes\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1941\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1942\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Nazi Agent]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Affairs of Martha]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Reunion in France]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1943\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Young Ideas]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1944\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Canterville Ghost (1944 film)|The Canterville Ghost]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1946\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Two Smart People]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[A Letter for Evie]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1947\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1948\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Naked City]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1949\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Thieves' Highway]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1950\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Night and the City]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1955\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Rififi]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| C\u00e9sar le Milanais\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1957\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[He Who Must Die]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1959\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Law (1959 film)|The Law]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1960\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Never on Sunday]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Homer Thrace\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1962\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Phaedra (film)|Phaedra]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Christo\n| Uncredited\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1964\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Topkapi (film)|Topkap\u0131]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Turkish cop\n| Uncredited\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1966\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[10:30 P.M. Summer]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1968\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Survival 1967]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Uptight (film)|Uptight]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1970\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Promise at Dawn]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| Ivan Mosjukine\n|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1974\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Rehearsal (1974 film)|The Rehearsal]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| Himself\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1978\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[A Dream of Passion]]''\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1980\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Circle of Two]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Portal|Biography}}\n*{{IMDb name|0202088|Jules Dassin}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080501163842/http://www.mkm-haifa.co.il/francais/chanson/dassin_photos.htm Family photos (French)]\n*[https://movies.nytimes.com/person/86774/Jules-Dassin Jules Dassin] at ''[[The New York Times]] Movies''\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2008/04/01/movies/01dassin.html New York Times obituary]\n*[http://www.wsws.org/en/articles/2008/04/dass-a03.html Obituary] on the ''[[World Socialist Web Site]]\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n88-660679}}\n\n{{Jules Dassin}}\n{{Prix de la mise en scene 1946\u20131959}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dassin, Jules}}\n[[Category:Films directed by Jules Dassin| ]]\n[[Category:Hollywood blacklist]]\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:English-language film directors]]\n[[Category:French-language film directors]]\n[[Category:German-language film directors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Communist Party USA]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Greece]]\n[[Category:Deaths from influenza]]\n[[Category:Infectious disease deaths in Greece]]\n[[Category:Naturalized citizens of Greece]]\n[[Category:People from Middletown, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Burials at the First Cemetery of Athens]]\n[[Category:American people of Ukrainian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Film directors from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Cannes Film Festival Award for Best Director winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Jules Dassin\n| image         = Joe and Jules Dassin 1970.jpg\n| caption       = Jules Dassin (right) with son Joe in Paris in 1970\n| birthname     = Julius Dassin\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date|1911|12|18}}\n| birth_place    = [[Middletown, Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{Death date and age|2008|3|31|1911|12|18}}\n| death_place    = [[Athens]], Greece\n| spouse        = {{marriage|B\u00e9atrice Launer<br>|1937|1962|end=divorced}}<br> {{marriage|[[Melina Mercouri]]<br>|1966|1994|end=died}}\n| children = [[Joe Dassin|Joseph Ira Dassin]]<br/>Richelle Dassin<br/>{{Interlanguage link multi|Julie Dassin|fr}}\n}}\n'''Julius''' \"'''Jules'''\" '''Dassin''' (December 18, 1911 \u2013 March 31, 2008) was an American film director, producer, writer and actor. He was a subject of the [[Hollywood blacklist]] in the [[Joseph McCarthy|McCarthy]] era, and subsequently moved to France, where he revived his career.\n\n== Biography ==\n===Early life===\nDassin was born in [[Middletown, Connecticut]], one of eight children of Berthe Vogel and Samuel Dassin, a barber. His parents were both [[Jewish]] immigrants from [[Odessa]], in modern-day [[Ukraine]].<ref>David B. Green, [https://www.haaretz.com/jewish/1911-director-who-paris-adored-is-born-1.5378392 This Day in Jewish History 1911: Blacklisted Director Who Became the Toast of Paris Is Born], [[Haaretz]], 18 December 2015. Retrieved 30 May 2018.</ref> Dassin grew up in Harlem and went to [[Morris High School (Bronx)|Morris High School]] in the [[Bronx]]. During his youth he attended [[Camp Kinderland]], the left-wing Yiddish youth camp. He joined the [[Communist Party USA]] in the 1930s and left it after the [[Molotov\u2013Ribbentrop Pact]] in 1939. \n\n===Early career===\nDassin started as an actor with the ARTEF (''[[Yiddish theatre|Yiddish Proletarian Theater]]'') company in New York. He collaborated on a film with [[Jack Skurnick]] that was uncompleted because of Skurnick's early death.\n\nIn 1940 he moved to Hollywood and became an assistant director at [[RKO Pictures]] before moving to [[MGM]] where he made short films including ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]'' (1941) which led to him being promoted to direct feature films.<ref>{{cite book | last = Katz | first = Ephraim | title = The Macmillan International Film Encyclopedia | publisher = Macmillan | location = New York | year = 1998 | isbn = 0-333-74037-8 |oclc=39216574 |edition=3rd |page=333}}</ref>\n\nDassin quickly became better known for his [[film noir|noir films]] ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]'' (1947), ''[[The Naked City]]'' (1948), and ''[[Thieves' Highway]]'' (1949), which helped him to become regarded as \"one of the leading American filmmakers of the postwar era.\"<ref name=\"Luther\">{{cite news|last=Luther|first=Claudia|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2008/apr/01/local/me-dassin1|title=Noir master directed caper classic 'Rififi'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 1, 2008|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Hollywood Blacklist===\n{{Main|Hollywood Blacklist}}\nDassin said [[Darryl F. Zanuck]] in 1948 called him into his office to inform him he would be blacklisted, but he still had enough time to make a movie for Fox.<ref>''[[Cineaste (magazine)|Cineaste]]'', [[Dan Georgakas]], spring 2007, p.72</ref>\nDassin was blacklisted in Hollywood during the production of ''[[Night and the City]]'' (1950).<ref>The film was shot in 1949, see {{cite web|last=Duncan|first=Paul|url=http://www.port-magazine.com/film/why-i-love-night-and-the-city-1950/|title=Why I Love: Night and the City (1950)|work=Port|date=July 2, 2014|accessdate=September 28, 2015}}</ref> He was not allowed on the studio property to edit or oversee the musical score for the film.<ref name=\"dassin_interview\">{{cite AV media|last=Dassin|first=Jules|medium=post-screening interview in DVD supplements|title=[[Night and the City]]|publisher=[[Criterion Collection]]|date=February 1, 2005}}</ref> He also had trouble finding work abroad, as U.S. distribution companies blacklisted the U.S. distribution of any European film associated with artists blacklisted in Hollywood. In 1952, after Dassin had been out of work for two years, actress [[Bette Davis]] hired him to direct her in the Broadway revue ''[[Two's Company (musical)|Two's Company]]''. The show closed early, however, and Dassin left for Europe. \n\n===Move to Europe===\nDassin did not work as a film director again until ''[[Rififi]]'' in 1955 (a French production), his most influential film and an early work in the [[heist film|\"heist film\" genre]].  He won the Best Director award for the film at the 1955 [[Cannes Film Festival]].\n\nIt inspired later heist films, such as ''[[Ocean's Eleven (1960 film)|Ocean's Eleven]]'' (1960).<ref name=\"Luther\"/> Another film it  inspired was Dassin's own heist film ''[[Topkapi (film)|Topkapi]]'' (1964), filmed in France and [[Istanbul, Turkey]] with his future second wife, [[Melina Mercouri]] and Oscar winner [[Peter Ustinov]].\n\nMost of Dassin's films in the decades following the blacklist are European productions.<ref name=\"Luther\"/> His prolific later career in Europe and the affiliation with Greece through his second wife, combined with a common pronunciation of his surname as \"Da-SAN\" in Europe, as opposed to \"DASS-in\" in the United States leads to a common misconception that he was a European director.<ref name=\"dassin_interview\"/>\n\n===Melina Mercouri===\nAt the Cannes Film Festival in May 1955 he met Melina Mercouri, Greek actress and wife of Panos Harokopos.<ref name=\"Luther\"/> At about the same time, he discovered the literary works of [[Nikos Kazantzakis]]; these two elements created a bond with Greece. Dassin next made ''[[He Who Must Die]]'' (1957) based on Kazantzakis' ''[[Christ Recrucified]]'' and in which Mercouri appeared. She went on to star in his ''[[Never on Sunday]]'' (1960) for which she won best actress at the Cannes Film Festival.<ref name=Skainews>{{in lang|el}} [http://www.skai.gr/master_story.php?id=77340 Skai News] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717003130/http://www.skai.gr/master_story.php?id=77340 |date=July 17, 2011 }}, \u0391\u03c0\u03b5\u03b2\u03af\u03c9\u03c3\u03b5 \u03bf \u0396\u03c5\u03bb \u039d\u03c4\u03b1\u03c3\u03ad\u03bd (''Jules Dassin died''), [http://www.google.com/translate?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.skai.gr%2Fmaster_story.php%3Fid%3D77340&langpair=el%7Cen&ie=UTF8 English (machine translation)] Retrieved on April 1, 2008.</ref> She then starred in his next three films \u2013 ''[[Phaedra (film)|Phaedra]]'' (1962), ''[[Topkapi (film)|Topkapi]]'' (1964) and ''[[10:30 P.M. Summer]]'' (1966).\n\nHe divorced his first wife, B\u00e9atrice Launer, in 1962 and married Mercouri in 1966. She later starred in his ''[[Promise at Dawn]]'' (1970).  During filming, Dassin broke both his legs.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|page=2|date=October 8, 1969|title=Dassin Breaks Both Legs In Freak Studio Accident}}</ref>\n\n===Affiliation with Greece===\nDassin was considered a major [[Philhellene]] to the point of Greek officials describing him as a \"first generation Greek\". Along with Mercouri, he opposed the [[Greek military junta]]. \n\nThe couple had to leave Greece after the [[Greek military junta of 1967\u201374|colonels' coup]] in 1967. In 1970 they were accused of having financed an attempt to overthrow the dictatorship, but the charges were quickly dropped.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Dassin and Mercouri lived in New York City during the 1970s; then, when the military dictatorship in Greece fell in 1974, they returned to Greece and lived out their lives there. In 1974 he and Mercouri made ''[[The Rehearsal (1974 film)|The Rehearsal]]'' about the junta. \n\nWhile Mercouri became involved with politics and won a parliamentary seat, Dassin stayed with movie-making in Europe. In 1982 he was a member of the jury at the [[34th Berlin International Film Festival]].<ref name=\"Berlinale\">{{cite web |url=http://www.berlinale.de/en/archiv/jahresarchive/1984/04_jury_1984/04_Jury_1984.html |title=Berlinale: 1984 Juries |accessdate=November 21, 2010 |work=berlinale.de}}</ref>\n\n=== Death ===\nDassin died from complications of [[influenza]] at the age of 96; he was survived by his two daughters and his grandchildren. Upon his death, the Greek prime minister, [[Costas Karamanlis]], released a statement: \"Greece mourns the loss of a rare human being, a significant artist and true friend. His passion, his relentless creative energy, his fighting spirit and his nobility will remain unforgettable.\"<ref name=\"Luther\"/>\n\nA major supporter of the return of the [[Elgin Marbles|Parthenon Marbles]] to Athens, for which he established the ''Melina Mercouri Institution'' in her memory after her death in 1994, he died a few months before the opening ceremony of the [[New Acropolis Museum]].<ref name=Skainews/>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:Dasin family 1970.jpg|thumb|Joe and Jules Dassin with B\u00e9atrice Launer in Paris in 1970]]\nDassin was married twice.  Prior to his marriage to Mercouri, in 1937 he married [[B\u00e9atrice Launer]], a New York\u2013born, {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} Jewish\u2013American {{Citation needed|date=June 2011}} violinist (aka Beatrice Launer-Dassin; 1913\u20131994),<ref>[http://www.genealogybank.com/gbnk/ssdi/doc/ssdi/v1:112F47BE008D2836 Beatrice Dassin]. Genealogy Bank. Retrieved on July 26, 2015.</ref> a graduate of the [[Juilliard School]] of Music.<ref>[http://www.juilliard.edu/libraryarchives/pdfs/baton/LoRes/V10N8low.pdf The Juilliard School of Music, \"The Baton\", p. 12] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100528000637/http://www.juilliard.edu/libraryarchives/pdfs/baton/LoRes/V10N8low.pdf |date=May 28, 2010 }}</ref> They divorced in 1962. Their children were Joseph Ira Dassin, better known as [[Joe Dassin]] (1938\u201380), a popular French singer in the 1970s; songwriter Richelle \"Rickie\" Dassin (born 1940); and actress\u2013singer Julie Dassin (born 1944; also known as Julie D.).<ref>[https://archive.is/20120728181518/http://rateyourmusic.com/artist/julie_d_ Julie D.]. Rateyourmusic.com (July 19, 1945). Retrieved on July 26, 2015.</ref>\n\n==Preservation==\nThe Academy Film Archive preserved Jules Dassin's film ''Night and the City'', including the British and pre-release versions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Preserved Projects|url=http://www.oscars.org/academy-film-archive/preserved-projects?title=&filmmaker=jules+dassin&category=All&collection=All|website=Academy Film Archive}}</ref>\n\nIn 2000, Rialto pictures restored and released ''Rififi'' theatrically.  It was subsequently released on home video through [[The Criterion Collection]] and [[Arrow Films]].\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:33px;\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Title\n! colspan=\"6\"|Credited as\n|-\n! width=65 | [[Film director|Director]]\n! width=65 | [[Film producer|Producer]]\n! width=65 |[[Screenwriter|Writer]]\n! width=65 |[[Actor]]\n! Role\n! Notes\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1941\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Tell-Tale Heart (1941 film)|The Tell-Tale Heart]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 1942\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Nazi Agent]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Affairs of Martha]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Reunion in France]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1943\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Young Ideas]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1944\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Canterville Ghost (1944 film)|The Canterville Ghost]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 1946\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Two Smart People]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[A Letter for Evie]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1947\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Brute Force (1947 film)|Brute Force]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1948\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[The Naked City]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1949\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| ''[[Thieves' Highway]]''\n| {{yes}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|| 1950\n| style=\"text-alig